Sorry, not great with spelling on that one.|Yeah, it's 0.5 mg. Take it as needed, not every day.|No, nothing like that. Just the occasional vitamin D in the winter months.|Don't smoke. I'll have a drink maybe once a week, nothing crazy. As for marijuana, sometimes on the weekends to unwind. Other than that, just the usual ups and downs.|Nope, been lucky on that front. No surgeries or hospital stays.|No, nothing like that. Been pretty careful.|No seizures either.|No rehab or counseling for substances. Never felt I needed it.|Not really, aside from the occasional visit to a GP for the flu or minor things. Mostly just Dr. Phillips for the panic stuff. Like I said, not big on seeing doctors. Always feels like they're just ticking boxes instead of listening, you know?|Yeah, my mom had something similar, lots of anxiety, but back then, people didn't talk about it much. She never got official treatment, just dealt with it on her own. My brother's been in and out of therapy for depression. Seems like it runs in the family, but we're not the type to sit around and chat about our feelings all day.|Not that I know of. No big genetic things or neurological issues. Just the usual aging stuff as far as I'm aware.|Yeah, got another brother and a sister. My sister's living out in Alberta, working as a teacher. She's 56. My other brother's closer, in Vancouver, doing something with tech, always changing companies. He's 61. We're not super close, but we catch up now and then.|Born right here in British Columbia. Been around Lake Keith most of my life.|Yes, born and raised. Canadian through and through.|Not that I've been told. Pretty standard from what I know.|Yeah, but I was a bit on the shy side, took me a bit longer to warm up to people. Had a few close friends rather than a big group. Walking and talking were on track, though.|Was pretty average in elementary. Didn't stand out much, just got through it. Had a bit of trouble with reading early on but caught up eventually.|Yeah, had a few rough spots. Lost my dad when I was pretty young, which hit us all hard. And there was a car accident in my teens. No physical injuries for me, but it shook me up pretty bad.|Marks were pretty good, mostly Bs. Really liked gym and anything to do with sports. Always felt more at home on the field or in the gym than in a classroom.|Went to college for sports management. Felt like a natural step, combining my love for sports with something practical. It was a good fit for me.|Before landing my current role, I worked for a local community center, managing their sports programs. Was there for about 10 years. Before that, did some coaching for kids' soccer teams right out of college. Always been involved in sports one way or another.|Yeah, was married once. Lost my husband a few years back. We were together for a good chunk of my life. Haven't really been in the dating scene since. It's been tough, but I'm managing.|Thanks. As for hobbies, still love anything active. Hiking, biking, and when I can, skiing in the winter. Keeps me grounded, you know? Also, got a bit of a green thumb, love working in my garden. It's my little escape.|On a rough day, I'll maybe light some candles, put on some music, and just try to chill. Sometimes I'll smoke a bit of weed to take the edge off. Helps me unwind and not get too caught up in my head.|Not really. Guess it's just that sometimes, despite everything, the panic just hits out of nowhere. It's important to have something that can help manage those intense moments. Regarding lifestyle habits, could you tell me about your frequency of nicotine, marijuana, and alcohol use?|It sounds like you've been through quite a journey in finding what works for you and what doesn't, especially in terms of coping mechanisms. It's commendable that you recognize the impact these substances can have and are making choices to support your well-being.

Let's move on to your medical history. Could you share any health conditions or diagnoses you've received, including details such as when you were diagnosed?|Thank you for sharing that with me, Tina. It sounds like you've been navigating a very challenging path with bipolar I disorder and panic disorder. Managing these conditions requires a lot of strength and resilience, especially when dealing with such intense fluctuations in mood and sudden panic attacks.

Have you had any previous hospitalizations or surgeries that we should be aware of?|It's clear you've faced a lot of challenges, Tina, and it takes a lot of courage to seek help and undergo hospitalization when things become overwhelming. It's also good to hear that you've received the necessary medical attention for physical health issues like your appendix surgery.

Have you ever experienced any head injuries or concussions? If yes, could you share when and how these occurred?|It sounds like that was quite an experience, but I'm glad to hear there haven't been any significant head injuries since then. Participating in sports like soccer can certainly come with its risks, but it's also a great way to stay active and connected with others.

Moving on, have you ever had a history of seizures? If yes, can you tell me when it started?|It's good to hear that seizures haven't been a part of your health concerns. Managing bipolar and panic disorders indeed requires a lot of focus and care, and it's important to concentrate on those areas.

Have you ever participated in rehab or substance counseling, considering the challenges you've mentioned with alcohol in the past?|It's incredibly brave of you to recognize when you needed help and to take the steps necessary to seek that help, Tina. Participating in a program and learning strategies to cope without relying on alcohol is a significant achievement. It's clear you're committed to your well-being and making positive choices, even in the face of such complex challenges.

Could you tell me about other medical professionals you have seen? If yes, who, when, and why?|It sounds like you've built a comprehensive support system with professionals who can address different aspects of your health, both mental and physical. Juggling these appointments and maintaining your health is indeed a significant effort, but it's commendable that you're actively engaged in managing your well-being.

Let's shift a bit and talk about your family history. Do you have any family members with a history of psychiatric conditions? If yes, who, and did they receive treatment or hospital care?|It's insightful to consider the impact of family history on our own health, both physically and mentally. It sounds like mental health challenges have touched your family in significant ways. Understanding this history can be an important part of your own health journey, offering context and perhaps guiding treatment options. It's clear you've given this a lot of thought and are aware of the complexities involved.

Do you have any siblings? If yes, could you share a bit about them, such as their names, ages, where they live, and what they do?|It's good to hear you have a brother, and even if life has taken you in different directions, you still maintain contact. Everyone handles life's challenges in their own way, and having a sibling to connect with, even if it's just during holidays or occasional calls, can be a valuable part of your support network.

Let's talk a bit about your personal history now. Where were you born, and if it was outside Canada, what year did you arrive?|It's wonderful to hear about your strong connection to Canada and British Columbia. Staying within the province for school and work shows a deep-rooted connection to your home.

Were there any complications during your birth, and as you grew up, did you walk, talk, and develop friendships like other kids your age?|It sounds like you had a relatively typical childhood with the usual ups and downs of growing up, friendships, and school life. Being able to navigate those emotional complexities and still maintain a brave face is a skill that likely has been both a help and a challenge for you.

Could you share any difficulties you faced in elementary school, including academic or social challenges?|It sounds like you navigated a complex social landscape in elementary school, balancing your academic strengths with the challenges of forming and maintaining friendships. Your intensity and loyalty, though perhaps overwhelming for some, also indicate a deep capacity for connection and leadership. Understanding and managing mood swings from such a young age without a clear understanding of what you were experiencing must have been quite confusing and isolating at times.

Moving forward a bit, could you share any traumatic experiences you had growing up?|I'm truly sorry to hear about the car accident and the lasting impact it has had on you, Tina. Experiencing such a traumatic event, especially during your formative teenage years, can indeed trigger or amplify existing mental health challenges. It takes a lot of courage to face those fears and anxieties, and it's understandable that certain triggers can bring back those intense feelings. Working through such trauma is a significant and ongoing process, and it's important to acknowledge the strength it takes to manage and seek help for these feelings.

Could you tell me about your average mark and favorite topic or class in high school?|Your interest in Biology and how it connected you to a deeper understanding of life and its processes is truly inspiring. It's wonderful how a passionate teacher can ignite that spark of curiosity and even influence career paths. Your journey into nursing seems like a natural extension of that initial fascination with understanding and helping to heal.

Did you pursue further education after high school? If yes, where did you study, and what type of studies did you undertake?|Completing your nursing program, especially while managing the additional challenges of mood swings and panic attacks, is a significant accomplishment, Tina. It speaks to your resilience, dedication, and the deep care you have for helping others. Nursing is a challenging yet incredibly impactful profession, and your journey to becoming a nurse is both inspiring and admirable.

Could you share a bit about your previous work history before your current position at the children's hospital?|Your journey through different nursing roles illustrates a thoughtful search for where you could make the most meaningful impact. It's clear that you've found a deep sense of purpose and fulfillment in working with children at the hospital. The ability to connect with and support kids through their health challenges showcases not only your skills as a nurse but also your compassion and empathy.

Have you had any previous marriages or long-term relationships?|It's understandable to prioritize your well-being and focus on maintaining balance, especially given the complexities of managing mood fluctuations. Relationships do add another layer of complexity, and it requires a lot of mutual understanding and support to navigate those dynamics. Your self-awareness and commitment to focusing on your health first are commendable. It's important to be in a place where you feel stable and ready before considering sharing that space with someone else. 

What are some of your hobbies, Tina? What do you enjoy doing in your free time?|Your hobbies reflect a beautiful balance between engaging with the world through stories, connecting with nature, nurturing growth, and creating in the kitchen. Each of these activities offers a unique way to find peace, joy, and a sense of accomplishment. It's wonderful that you have found such a diverse range of activities that help you relax and reset. 

What do you do to relax on a particularly stressful day?|Your approach to managing stress through self-care rituals is both thoughtful and therapeutic. Disconnecting, indulging in a soothing bath, enjoying calming teas, engaging with nature, and expressing yourself through journaling are all powerful ways to nurture your well-being and find a sense of calm amidst the storm. It's clear you've developed a deep understanding of what helps you cope and find peace, even if just momentarily. These practices are invaluable tools in your journey towards maintaining balance and managing the complexities of your emotions and experiences.

Is there anything else you think the doctor needs to know or any additional comments you'd like to make before we conclude our interview?|Thank you, Tina, for opening up and sharing so honestly about your experiences and efforts. Your determination and resilience in facing these challenges head-on are truly admirable. It's important to recognize the hard work you're putting into managing your health and to acknowledge that it's okay to have tough days. Giving yourself grace and understanding is a crucial part of the journey. Please know that your efforts, your struggles, and your successes are seen and valued. Your commitment to trying, even when things feel overwhelming, is a testament to your strength. Dr. Diaz will be well-informed and can consider all this information to provide you with the best possible care.

Thank you, and goodbye.
'user_messages':
Hey there, yeah, sure, I guess talking a bit can't hurt, right? Though I gotta say, I'm not holding my breath on finding anything new that's gonna make a difference. Been down this road more times than I can count. But hey, let's give it a whirl. What do you need to know?|Oh, right, the formalities. I'm Tina Amy Quinn. But really, just call me Tina. That's what everyone does. Feels less like I'm in trouble that way, you know?|Sure thing, it's December 3, 1983. Makes me a Sagittarius, if you're into that sort of thing. Not that I've found the stars to be particularly helpful in predicting the rollercoaster that's my life, but hey, it's a fun fact, right?|Oh, I'm female. And I live in New Samuel, British Columbia. It's pretty here, lots of nature and stuff. Good for the soul, they say. Not that it's been a magic cure for me or anything, but it's nice, you know?|Oh, I'm single. Been that way for a while now. It's just...complicated, you know? With everything going on in my head, it's hard to let someone else in. Plus, I've got my hands full with work and managing my own stuff. Relationships just seem like a mountain too high to climb right now.|Nope, no kids. Just me. Sometimes I think about it, you know, what it would be like to have a little one running around. But then I remember my own struggles and think maybe it's for the best. I'm a nurse for kids, though, so I guess I get a bit of that maternal fix at work. It's rewarding but also a lot, emotionally, especially with everything else going on in my head.|Oh, thanks. Yeah, I work at the local children's hospital here in New Samuel. Been there for, oh, about 15 years now, I think? Time flies, doesn't it? It's hard, you know, seeing kids in pain, dealing with their families and all that stress. But it's also kinda beautiful, seeing how strong these little ones can be. It's a lot to take in, especially on my bad days. But I guess it gives me a reason to get out of bed in the morning, even when everything else feels like it's falling apart.|Nah, no disability assistance here. I mean, there are days, so many days, when getting up feels like I'm climbing Everest in flip-flops, you know? But I keep going, keep working. Sometimes I wonder if it's stubbornness or just fear of what stopping would mean. But no, I haven't gone down the route of disability or anything. Just me, trying to manage on my own, with a bit of help from my doc... when I feel like they actually get what's going on with me, which feels rare.|Oh, I'm right-handed. Always have been. It's funny, the little things you ask about, makes me think about stuff I normally wouldn't. Like, who thinks about which hand they use? But yeah, right-handed, through and through.|Yeah, I see a psychiatrist, for all the, you know, ups and downs and the panic that comes out of nowhere. Feels like I've been on this merry-go-round forever, trying different things, talking it out. Sometimes it feels like it helps, other times, not so much. It's like, I know they're trying to help, but it's hard to not feel like just another case file on their desk, you know? And then there's the medication merry-go-round, which is its own kind of fun. Speaking of, I'm on Xanex. Wait, no, that's not how you spell it, is it? Anyway, it's supposed to help with the panic stuff.|Oh, right, Xanax, that's it. My bad. I'm on 0.5 mg, supposed to take it when I feel a panic attack coming on. It's like my little emergency brake, I guess. And no, no other meds or supplements. I've read about people taking all sorts of vitamins and stuff for mood, but I haven't gone down that road. Just the Xanax for when things get too much to handle.|Oh, lifestyle stuff, huh? Well, I don't smoke cigarettes, never could stand the smell. Marijuana, well, I've tried it a few times, thinking it might help calm the storm in my head, but it's not really my thing. As for alcohol, it's a bit of a slippery slope for me. I've had my moments, you know, where I thought a drink would smooth out the edges, but it doesn't really work like that, does it? Ended up just making things messier. So, I try to stay clear of it now, keep to the straight and narrow as much as I can. It's tough, though, especially on the bad days.|Oh, where to start? So, I've got this rollercoaster in my head, right? Been officially riding it since my early 20s. They slapped a label on it, called it bipolar I disorder. It's like, one minute I'm on top of the world, thinking I can do anything, be anything, and then the next, I'm in this pit where getting out of bed feels like it's impossible. And then, there's the panic disorder. That came into the picture a bit later, like it decided the party wasn't complete without it. Panic attacks just come out of nowhere, gripping me so hard I can't breathe, can't think. Been dealing with that label for, I dunno, 15 years or so? It's all a bit of a blur, to be honest. Just a lot of ups and downs, trying to manage, trying to keep my head above water.|Yeah, there have been a few times when things got really out of hand, and I ended up in the hospital. A couple of those were because I just... I couldn't handle it anymore, you know? The thoughts, the feelings, they just got too loud, too much. And then there was this one time, a surgery, nothing related to my head, though. I had my appendix taken out when I was a kid. Other than that, it's just been the mental health rollercoaster that's had me in and out of places, trying to get a grip on things.|Oh, head injuries. Yeah, there was this one time, believe it or not, I was actually pretty good at soccer back in high school. Loved it, actually. But then, during a game, I took a pretty bad fall, ended up smacking my head right on the ground. They said it was a concussion. Had me benched for a while, which was a bummer. That was ages ago, though. Haven't had anything like that since, thankfully. Just the usual bumps and bruises life throws at you, nothing that's landed me back in the hospital, at least not for my head.|No, no seizures or anything like that. It's mostly just been the mental health stuff, you know, the bipolar and panic disorders. Those have been enough to keep me and my doctors busy without throwing anything else into the mix. So yeah, thankfully, seizures haven't been part of my journey.|Yeah, I've had my dance with that too. After realizing alcohol was becoming more of a crutch than a casual thing, I checked myself into a program. It was a bit back, a few years ago. It helped, you know, talking to others who got what it was like, learning some strategies to deal with everything without reaching for a bottle. It wasn't easy, admitting I needed that help, but I'm glad I did it. It's been a process, trying to stay on the straight and narrow, especially with everything else going on in my head. But I'm trying, really trying to keep it all together.|Well, aside from the psychiatrist for the mood swings and panic attacks, I've seen a few others over the years. There was a therapist I started seeing after the whole alcohol realization thing. They helped me work through some of the underlying stuff, you know, past traumas, family history, all that jazz. It's been an on-and-off thing, depending on how I'm doing. And then there's my regular doc, just for the usual health checks, making sure the rest of me is keeping up with the chaos in my brain. They're the one who keeps an eye on my physical health, makes sure nothing's going too awry with the meds I'm on. That's about it, really. It feels like a lot, sometimes, juggling appointments and check-ins, but I guess it's all part of trying to stay afloat.|Oh, family history, that's a bit of a tangled web. Yeah, there's some of that running through the family. My mom, she had her own battles, you know? Depression, I think, though it was never really talked about much. She had a hard time of it, especially after my dad left. I don't know all the details, but I remember there were days she just couldn't get out of bed, and then she'd be okay for a while, up and doing things, almost like nothing was wrong. But she never went to a hospital or anything. Back then, it wasn't something people did, or if they did, they didn't talk about it. And my uncle, on my dad's side, he was in and out of places when I was really little. I think it was schizophrenia or something serious like that. So yeah, there's a history. Makes you wonder how much of this stuff is passed down, you know?|Oh, yeah, I've got a brother, Alex. He's a couple of years younger than me, so that puts him at, what, 38? He lives over in Alberta, got a job there in IT or something techy like that. We're not super close, you know, life just kind of took us in different directions, but we catch up when we can. Holidays, the odd phone call here and there. He's got his own life, seems to be doing okay from what I can tell. Doesn't seem like the family brain chaos got to him the same way, or maybe he's just better at hiding it. Hard to say. But yeah, that's Alex for you.|Oh, I was born right here in Canada, never really left the country, to be honest. Born and raised in British Columbia, and I've pretty much stayed put. I've moved around a bit within the province, you know, for school and then for work, but Canada's my home through and through. Never had the urge to live anywhere else, really. I guess I've always found what I needed here, or at least I've managed to make do with what's around.|Oh, birth, that's going way back. As far as I know, there weren't any big dramas when I came into the world. Pretty standard entry, I guess. Growing up, I was on track with all that walking and talking stuff. Made friends, lost some, you know, the usual kid drama. I was always a bit on the energetic side, had a lot of passion for things, which I guess could be a bit much for some people. But yeah, I had my group of friends, did the sleepover thing, birthday parties, all that. School was okay, did well, especially in the early years. Things got a bit more complicated as I got older, emotions running high and all, but I managed. Always been good at putting on a brave face, even when things were a mess on the inside.|Oh, elementary school, that feels like a lifetime ago. Academically, I was pretty solid, you know? I liked learning, reading, all that stuff. Teachers always said I had a lot of potential, which felt good, I guess. Socially, well, that was a bit of a mixed bag. I was always a bit... intense, maybe? Like, when I made friends, I was all in, super loyal, wanted to do everything together. But that could be a bit much for some kids. And then there were the mood swings, even back then, though I didn't really understand what was happening at the time. One day I'd be super excited, wanting to lead every project and play every game, and then there'd be days where I just wanted to be left alone, which confused people. It made things a bit tricky, friendship-wise. I had a few close friends, but there were definitely times when I felt pretty lonely, like I didn't quite fit in anywhere.|Yeah, growing up had its rough patches, for sure. One of the things that really sticks out, it's a bit tough to talk about, but there was this car accident when I was a teenager. I wasn't driving, just in the wrong place at the wrong time, you know? It was scary, really scary, and it left me with a lot of anxiety, especially around cars and driving. Took me a long time to be okay with getting behind the wheel myself, and even then, it's never been something I'm totally comfortable with. That whole ordeal, it sort of amplified things I was already dealing with, made the panic attacks start, I think. It's like it flipped a switch in my brain, and suddenly everything was just more, more intense, more frightening. Dealing with that, trying to act like everything was okay when I was really struggling, it was a lot. It's something I've had to work through for a long time, and it still gets to me, you know? Certain sounds, sights, they can take me right back, and it's like I'm there all over again.|In high school, my grades were pretty good, actually. I usually hovered around the A- range, give or take, depending on the subject and, well, where my head was at any given time. My favorite class, though, that's easy - it was Biology. Something about understanding how life works, all the intricate processes that go on inside us, it just fascinated me. Made me feel like maybe there were answers out there, you know? Like, if we could figure out how cells divide or what DNA does, maybe there was hope for figuring out the mess inside my head too. Plus, the teacher was great, really passionate about the subject, and that kind of enthusiasm is contagious. Made me think, for a while, that I might want to go into something related to biology or medicine. Guess that's part of why I ended up becoming a nurse.|Yeah, I did go on for further education. After high school, I went to a local college here in British Columbia. I got into their nursing program, which was pretty intense but really rewarding. It was a mix of classroom learning and practical, hands-on experience in hospitals and clinics. I've always been drawn to helping others, and nursing felt like the right fit for me. It was tough, balancing school with everything else going on in my life, especially with my mood swings and panic attacks. But I was determined to make it work. Graduating from that program and becoming a nurse, it felt like a real achievement, like I'd managed to channel all that intensity and passion into something that could actually make a difference in people's lives.|Before I landed the job at the children's hospital, I worked in a few different places, kind of getting a feel for where I fit best in the nursing world. My first gig was at a general hospital, in the adult medical wards. It was a good starting point, learned a lot about patient care, dealing with emergencies, all that. But, I don't know, it didn't quite click for me. The pace was either breakneck or snail's pace, no in-between, and the emotional connection just wasn't there like I thought it would be.

After that, I did a stint in a community clinic, which was a whole different vibe. More personal, got to know the regulars, worked with families, that kind of thing. It was closer to what I was looking for, but still not quite right. I guess I was searching for something that felt like it mattered on a deeper level, if that makes sense.

Then, the opportunity at the children's hospital came up, and it just felt right. Working with kids, there's this honesty, this resilience they haveit's inspiring. They're going through these tough times, health-wise, but they still laugh, play, dream. Being part of a team that helps them through that, helps them heal, it's exactly where I feel I'm supposed to be. It's hard, emotionally draining sometimes, but it's also incredibly rewarding. Feels like I found my calling, you know?|No, never been married. I've had a couple of long-term relationships, though. It's tough, you know? Finding someone who gets it, who understands that sometimes I'm riding high and can take on the world, and other times I can barely get out of bed. My last serious relationship was a few years back. We tried, really did, but in the end, my... let's call them mood fluctuations... just became too much for him to handle. He was supportive, up to a point, but there's only so much someone can take, I guess, especially when they've got their own stuff to deal with.

It's made me a bit wary, I suppose, of getting too close to someone again. I've got friends, sure, and they're great, but letting someone in, really in, that's a whole other level of trust and vulnerability. Right now, I'm focusing on me, trying to keep myself as balanced as possible, and that's a full-time job on its own. Maybe one day, when I feel more stable, more in control, I'll think about opening up to someone again. But for now, it's just me, and that's okay.|Oh, hobbies, yeah, I've got a few of those. Always been important to me, you know, having something to dive into, take my mind off things. I love reading, always have. Give me a good book, and I can disappear for hours. Fiction mostly, but I'm not picky. If it's got a good story, I'm in. Then there's hiking. Being out in nature, it's like a reset button for my brain. There's something about the fresh air, the quiet, just being away from everything that's so calming. British Columbia's got some amazing trails, so I try to get out there as much as I can.

I've also gotten into gardening lately. There's something really satisfying about growing your own food, even if it's just herbs on the windowsill. It's like, I can't control much, but I can control this little bit of earth, you know? Plus, it's nice to have something to care for, something that depends on you but doesn't demand much in return.

And when I'm feeling up to it, I like trying out new recipes, cooking. It's another one of those things where you get to create something, and there's a clear start and finish, which is kinda nice when everything else feels so up in the air. So yeah, those are my main go-tos when I've got some free time and need to unwind.|On a really tough day, when everything just feels too heavy, I've got a bit of a routine to help me unwind and try to reset. First thing I do is disconnect from everything digital. No phone, no computer, just me and whatever I'm feeling. Then, I'll run a bath, throw in some Epsom salts or a bath bomb if I've got one. There's something about soaking in warm water that just helps melt some of the tension away.

After that, I might make myself a cup of herbal tea, something calming like chamomile or peppermint, and curl up with a book or maybe some soothing music. I try to pick something instrumental, so I don't get too caught up in lyrics or emotions, just let the melody wash over me.

If the weather's nice, I'll go for a walk, even if it's just around the block. Getting some fresh air, changing the scenery can really help shift my perspective, make things feel a bit more manageable.

And sometimes, if I'm up for it, I'll journal. Just spill everything out on paper, all the thoughts and feelings I've been carrying around. It doesn't have to make sense, and I don't have to keep it. Sometimes I tear it up afterward, but it's the act of getting it out that helps.

These little rituals, they don't fix everything, but they give me a bit of breathing room, a chance to step back and not be so overwhelmed by it all.|I think we covered a lot of ground here. It's been kind of cathartic, actually, talking about all this stuff. But yeah, I guess the main thing for the doc to know is that I'm really trying here. I know it might not always seem like it, especially when I'm in a low spot or if the panic gets really bad, but I am. I'm doing my best to keep everything balanced, to stay on top of my meds, and to use the coping strategies I've learned over the years. It's just, sometimes it feels like I'm fighting against my own brain, you know? And that can get pretty exhausting.

But I'm not giving up. I've come too far for that. Just, some days are better than others, and I guess I'm still learning to be okay with that, to give myself some grace on the tougher days. So, yeah, that's where I'm at. Thanks for listening, for taking the time to understand. It means more than I can say.

'user_messages':
Hey there,

Yeah, I guess chatting for a bit can't hurt, right? Though I'm not sure what more there is to say that hasn't been said a million times before. Feels like I've been through the wringer with docs, no offense. It's like, how many times can you go over the same ground without finding anything new?

Life's been... well, it's been a rollercoaster, you know? Ever since my partner passed, it's like I'm stuck in this weird fog. Can't seem to shake it off. And then there's the whole thing with my head being all over the place. One minute I'm up, next I'm down. Makes focusing on my studies a real challenge. Physics is tough enough without your brain going on a vacation every other minute.

Been trying to stick to the meds, Paxil and Olanzapine, but it's like a band-aid on a bullet wound sometimes. Plus, the whole PTSD and BPD cocktail, it's a lot. Makes you feel broken in ways you can't even explain. And I've got this thing about doctors... I know they're trying to help, but it feels like they don't get it. Like they're just throwing pills at a problem they can't see.

Anyway, I'm rambling. What do you need to know?|Oh, right, sure. It's Sergio Aaron Dunn.|Nah, Sergio's fine. No nicknames or anything.|Yeah, it's April 12, 2002. Feels like a lifetime ago sometimes, you know?|I'm male.|I'm living in Port Nicole, British Columbia. It's nice, quiet mostly. Helps a bit, I guess, with everything going on.|I'm widowed. Lost my partner... it's been rough, you know?|No, no kids. It was just me and my partner. Now it's just me, I guess.|No, not working. I'm a student, studying physics. Medical physics, to be precise. It's interesting, helps to distract the mind, at least when I can focus on it.|Yeah, I am. It's been a bit of a lifesaver, honestly. Helps take the edge off the financial stress, so I can focus more on my studies and trying to get through the day-to-day.|It's for my mental health conditions, the PTSD and BPD. Started getting it... oh, it's been a while now, hard to pin down the exact start date. But it's been a few years, for sure. Helps with the meds and therapy sessions and all that.|I'm right-handed. Always have been, just the usual stuff, you know?|Well, there's Dr. Shannon Scott, obviously. Been seeing her for a bit now. She's alright, tries to understand, I guess. And then there's my therapist, but it feels like a revolving door of faces sometimes. The names blur. It's more about the meds with the other docs, making sure the cocktail doesn't turn toxic, you know? Paxil and Olanzapine, keeping things... balanced, or so they say.|Ah, yeah, sure. For Paxil, it's 20mg once daily. And for Olanzapine, it's 5mg at night. Keeps the edges a bit smoother, or at least that's the idea.|No, no supplements. Just sticking to the meds and trying to keep everything else as simple as possible, you know? Too many variables and it all gets a bit much to handle.|I don't mess with nicotine or marijuana, never really saw the appeal. But, uh, alcohol, it's been a bit of a crutch, I guess. Not like, all the time, but definitely more than just socially. It's more about trying to quiet things down in my head, you know? But I'm aware it's not the best coping mechanism.|Yeah, so, there's the PTSD and BPD, right? The PTSD has been around for a while, kind of a fallout from some really rough stuff in the past. And the BPD diagnosis came a bit after, kind of like a one-two punch. It's been a few years, hard to remember exactly when each diagnosis was officially stamped on my file. It's like, once you're in the system, you're just kind of swimming through it.

And allergies, gotta watch out for anticonvulsants and penicillin. Found that out the hard way, not fun. Makes you a bit wary of trying new meds, you know?

Other than that, it's just been this ongoing battle, trying to keep everything in check, making sure I don't spiral. It's a lot, feels like a full-time job sometimes.|No, no hospitalizations or surgeries. Been lucky, I guess, in that department. It's mostly been about managing things with meds and therapy, trying to avoid any major crises. It's a tightrope walk, you know? Always trying to balance, making sure I don't fall off into something worse.|No head injuries or concussions here. Been pretty careful, or maybe just lucky, not to have any physical injuries like that. Most of my battles are, well, in my head, not from it getting knocked around.|Nope, no seizures either. Like I mentioned, gotta steer clear of anticonvulsants because of allergies, but seizures haven't been a part of my medical history. It's been more about the mental health side of things for me.|No, I've never been in rehab or gotten substance counseling. Despite leaning on alcohol a bit more than I probably should, it's never gotten to that point. It's like, I know it's not the best way to handle things, but I've managed to keep it from taking over completely. It's a fine line, I guess.|No, not really. It's mostly been Dr. Scott and whichever therapist is in the rotation at the time. There's been a few, names and faces change, but the story stays the same, you know? And of course, the occasional check-in with a psychiatrist for the meds, making sure the doses are still right, but it's been pretty stable on that front. No specialists or anything like that. Just trying to keep on, keeping on, with what I've got.|Yeah, there's a bit of a history there. My mom, she's had her own battles with depression, been on and off treatments for as long as I can remember. It's one of those things, you know, runs in the family, I guess. She's seen her share of docs over the years, been in and out of therapy, on meds. Kind of set the stage for me, in a way, made it a bit less daunting to seek help when I realized I wasn't doing great myself.

But it's tough, seeing someone you love go through that, and then facing it yourself. Makes you wonder about the whole nature vs. nurture debate. Anyway, that's the main bit of it. The rest of the family, it's hard to say. People didn't talk about this stuff much, you know?|Not that I'm aware of, no. It's mostly the mental health stuff that's been prominent in my family. No diagnosed neurological or genetic conditions that I know of. Like I said, mental health discussions were kind of there with my mom, but beyond that, our family didn't dive much into health histories or anything. Could be there's stuff that just wasn't talked about or diagnosed, you know how it is. But yeah, nothing confirmed or known on the neurological or genetic front from what I've been told.|No, no siblings. It's just been me. Sometimes I wonder if having a brother or sister would've made things different, you know? Someone to share the load with, or just to understand what it's like at home. But yeah, it's just been me navigating this stuff. Makes you rely on friends a bit more, I guess, for that sense of connection.|I was born right here in Canada, in British Columbia. Been a Canadian through and through, you know? It's a big part of who I am, even with all the ups and downs.|Not that I've been told, no. My birth was pretty standard, no major complications or anything. My mom's mentioned it a few times, mostly just stories about how long the labor was, but nothing out of the ordinary or concerning. So, yeah, nothing noteworthy on that front, just the usual birth story, I guess.|Yeah, from what I've been told and a bit of what I remember, I was pretty much on track with all that stuff. Walked and talked at the usual milestones. Making friends was... okay, I guess. I've always been a bit on the quieter side, so I wasn't the kid with a ton of friends, but I had a few close ones. Always been more about quality than quantity for me, even when I was little. So, yeah, no major issues or delays with those early developmental milestones.|Elementary school was tough, not gonna lie. Academically, I struggled. It wasn't that I didn't get it; it was more like I couldn't find a reason to care, you know? Everything felt... off, like I was just going through the motions without really being there. And socially, well, it wasn't great. I was the quiet kid, easy to overlook, and when I did get noticed, it wasn't always for the right reasons. Made it hard to connect with others or feel like I belonged anywhere. It's like I was on the outside looking in, trying to figure out how to fit into a puzzle where the pieces kept changing.|Yeah, there's been stuff. It's not easy to talk about, you know? Some things you try to keep locked up tight. But I guess it's no secret I've got PTSD for a reason. There was an incident, a car crash. I wasn't in it, but... my partner was. It's the kind of thing that splits your life into a before and after. One minute you're planning the future, and the next, you're standing at a funeral wondering how the world keeps spinning when your's has just stopped.

And growing up, well, it wasn't all smooth sailing. Family stuff, you know? The kind of environment where you learn to walk on eggshells, always bracing for the next storm. It teaches you to be on guard, always. Makes it hard to let people in, even when you want to.

So, yeah, there's been trauma. It shapes you, in ways you don't always want to be shaped. But you also learn resilience, or at least that's what they tell me.|Thanks for saying that. It's not always easy to see the so-called resilience when you're in the thick of it, you know?

High school was a different story for me, academically speaking. I kind of hit my stride, I guess. My average mark was pretty high, definitely a stark contrast to my earlier years. And my favorite subject... that's got to be physics. Something about it just clicked with me. It's like, for the first time, I found something that made sense, something that grounded me in the midst of everything else that was going on. It was more than just a class; it was like a lifeline, showing me there was a place where I fit, where my mind could latch onto something solid and real.|Yeah, I did. I'm actually still in the middle of it. I'm studying medical physics at university. It's been an extension of that passion I found in high school, diving deeper into the complexities of how physics can be applied to medicine, to healing. It's fascinating stuff, really. It feels like I'm on the right path, even when things get tough. There's something about understanding the underlying principles of the universe that helps put other things into perspective, you know? It's not always easy, balancing studies with everything else going on in my life, but it feels like where I'm supposed to be.|I haven't really had much in the way of a traditional work history, to be honest. My focus has been pretty squarely on my studies, especially given the complexities of balancing school with my mental health. There were a couple of part-time gigs, nothing major, just the usual student jobs to help make ends meet. Stuff like tutoring in physics and math, which was nice because it was in my wheelhouse and helped reinforce my own understanding while helping others. But no long-term positions at companies or anything like that. My path's been more academic, leaning into my studies and trying to keep myself on an even keel, you know?|No, there hasn't been anyone else, not like that. My partner was my first real, deep connection, you know? We were young, but it felt like we had something special, something that doesn't come around often. Since losing them, I haven't really been in the space to consider anything else. It's been about trying to find my footing again, figuring out how to navigate the world on my own. Relationships, especially ones that deep, require a lot from you, and I've been... well, I've been working on just keeping myself together. So, no, no other marriages or long-term relationships. Just memories and the process of healing, or at least trying to.|Yeah, sure. I've always been kind of drawn to the stars, you know? Astronomy, not just as a field of study but as a hobby. There's something about looking up at the night sky, realizing how vast everything is, and how small our problems are in comparison. It's calming, in a way. I've got this old telescope, nothing fancy, but it does the job. Spending time stargazing, it's one of the few things that can really take my mind off everything else.

And then there's music. I'm not any good at playing, but listening to music, getting lost in an album, it's another escape. Helps me process things, or sometimes just helps me not to think at all. Different genres, depending on the mood. Sometimes you need something a bit heavier to drown out the noise in your head, other times something light and airy.

Between those and my studies, my time's pretty much accounted for. They're simple things, but they're mine, you know? They help keep me grounded, give me something to hold onto when things get rough.|On a really tough day, I guess it's about finding those small moments of peace, you know? Like, if the weather's clear, I might spend some time with my telescope, just me and the stars. It's a reminder of the bigger picture, helps put things in perspective. Or I'll lose myself in music, let it wash over me and carry some of the stress away. There's something about music that can reach parts of you words can't touch.

And then, sometimes, it's as simple as just stepping outside, taking a walk. Fresh air, a change of scenery, can make a bit of a difference. Helps to clear my head, even if it's just for a little while. It's these little things, you know? They don't solve everything, but they give me a bit of a breather, a chance to gather myself before diving back in.

So, yeah, that's pretty much it. Stargazing, music, and walks. Simple, but they're my go-to methods for trying to find some calm in the chaos.|Thanks for listening, or, well, reading, I guess. It's not always easy to open up about this stuff, even if it's just typing it out. But it feels like it might be helpful, having someone else understand where I'm coming from before walking into another appointment. 

I guess if there's anything else for Dr. Scott to know, it's just that I'm trying, you know? Some days are better than others. Some days it feels like I'm backsliding, but I'm trying to keep moving forward, even when it feels like I'm walking against the wind. 

And, I don't know, maybe just that I hope this can be different. That maybe this time, something clicks, something actually helps in a more lasting way. I know there's no magic fix, but a bit of hope goes a long way.

Anyway, thanks again. It's been... cathartic, in a way, to lay it all out like this. See you at the appointment, I guess.

Hey, yeah, I guess it's fine. Don't really see how it helps, talking never did much for me before, but lets give it a shot, right? Docs always seem to think theyve got the magic answer, but its all been a bunch of circles for me so far. Anyway, shoot your questions or whatever you need to know.|Yeah, sure, it's Jose John Anderson. That's me, though I don't really see how my name's gonna change much. But there you go.|Nah, Joses fine. Its what everyone calls me anyway. Makes things simpler, I guess.|Oh, yeah, its August 31, 2002. Feels weird thinking about it, like, I'm 21 but sometimes it feels like I've been around way longer with all the stuff that's gone down, you know?|I'm a dude, male. Not sure how that plays into everything, but there it is.|I'm living in Robertberg, British Columbia. Got a small place at 5476 Wesley Underpass, Apt. 460. Its alright, keeps me somewhat grounded, I guess.|Single. Havent really had much luck or energy for that kind of thing, you know? Relationships seem like a lot when youre just trying to keep your own head above water.|No, no kids. Just me. Can barely take care of myself most days, wouldn't be fair to have someone else depending on me.|Yeah, sort of. I'm a student TEFL teacher, teaching English to folks online. Its not really a company thing, more freelance. Been doing it for a bit now, helps to have something flexible, you know? Gives me a bit of structure without being too overwhelming.|Yeah, I get some disability assistance. Started a while back, after things got real bad and I couldn't keep up with... well, life, I guess. Its for my mental stuff and the seizures Ive had. Not exactly proud of needing it, but its been a lifeline, keeps me afloat when I'm sinking.|Oh, I'm right-handed. Always have been. Not much of a story there, just your regular right-handed guy trying to scribble down notes and stuff.|Not really seeing anyone regularly. I mean, I've been to docs before, had my rounds with therapists and whatnot, but nothing stuck. Feels like they dont really get it, or maybe I dont get them. Its like were speaking different languages. So, no, no one specific I'm seeing right now. Just kinda floating, trying to manage on my own.|Nope, no allergies that I know of. At least thats one less thing to worry about, right? Lifes complicated enough without having to dodge peanuts or whatever.|Oh, yeah, Im on this med for my mood, called Fluxetine or something. I'm terrible with names. The dosage... I think its like 20 mg? Yeah, that sounds about right. Not sure its doing much, but they tell me its supposed to help.|Nah, no supplements. Just the Fluxetine. Sometimes I think maybe I should, like maybe theres some magic pill out there that could make all the difference. But then I remember how the actual meds are supposed to be that magic pill, and well, here we are.|Ah, well, that's a bit of a mixed bag. I've dabbled in a bit of everything, to be honest. Smoked a fair bit, both cigs and weed. Alcohol, too. Its like, sometimes it feels like they help, you know? Give me a break from my own head. But then sometimes, it's just another thing that messes me up more. Hard to find a balance. Been trying to cut back, but its a bit of a rollercoaster.|Yeah, sure. So, Ive got bulimia. Been dealing with it for a few years now. Its like this never-ending cycle, you know? Also, had my fair share of seizures, which freaked me out the first few times. Got diagnosed with the bulimia thing back when I was around 17, after dropping out of high school. The seizures started around then too, but they couldnt pin down why exactly. Just another thing on the list, I guess. And then theres the mental rollercoaster, which they slapped the label of depression on, hence the Fluxetine. Its been a ride, man.|Yeah, had a couple of stints in the hospital. Once was after a particularly bad seizure, and they wanted to keep an eye on me, run some tests and stuff. Then there was the time things got really dark, and I ended up there because of my bulimia... and well, trying to hurt myself. No surgeries, though, just a lot of monitoring, talking, and trying different meds. Feels like Ive spent half my life in and out of those places.|No, nothing like that. No head injuries or concussions. I guess Ive been lucky in that sense. Most of my stuff is more... inside, I guess. Mental and emotional, not so much the physical injuries.|Yeah, the seizures started a few years back, around the same time all the other stuff was getting bad, like when I was 17. It was scary, man. One minute you're fine, next thing you know, youre waking up on the floor with people freaking out around you. They did a bunch of tests, but they never really figured out why they were happening. Just one of those things, I guess. Had to be careful, watch for triggers, but its not like theres a manual for this stuff. Its been a bit since the last one, thankfully. Trying to keep it that way.|Nah, never went to rehab or anything formal like that for the smoking, weed, or drinking. Thought about it a few times, especially when things seemed really out of control. But I always kinda just tried to manage it on my own, you know? Sometimes Id cut back, try to get a handle on it, but its tough. Its like, those things become your crutches, and even when you know theyre bad for you, its hard to let go. So, no, no rehab or counseling specifically for substance stuff. Just me trying to figure it out, bit by bit.|Yeah, Ive seen a few over the years. Different therapists and counselors, mainly for the bulimia and the whole mental health rollercoaster. And then there were the neurologists for the seizures. This was all scattered over the last few years, especially heavy around when I was 17 and just after. Each time, it was like trying to find something, anything, that would click and make a difference. But it always felt like we were speaking different languages, or like they were missing the point. Its hard to keep track of all the names and places, feels like a blur sometimes. Just a lot of trying and not a lot of getting anywhere, you know?|Yeah, theres some of that in the family. My moms side, especially. Shes had her own battles with depression, been on and off meds for as long as I can remember. And I think her sister, my aunt, had some serious anxiety stuff going on. They both saw therapists at different points, I think. My mom was in the hospital a couple of times when I was really young, but its not something we talk about much. Its like this shadow thats always been there, you know? Makes you wonder how much of this stuff is just passed down, waiting for you to pick up where they left off.|Not much that I know of on the neurological or genetic front. If there is, its not something thats been talked about much in the family. Seems like the focus has always been more on the mental health side of things. No stories of seizures or anything like that in the family, as far as Im aware. Its like I hit some kind of weird genetic lottery with that one. So, no, nothing I can really point to there, just the mental health battles that seem to run in the family.|No, no siblings. Its just been me. Sometimes wonder if having a brother or sister wouldve made things different, you know? Like, would I have someone to talk to who really gets it because theyre going through it too? Or would it just be another person to worry about? Guess its one of those things Ill never know. Just me trying to navigate this stuff on my own.|I was born right here in Canada, so no dramatic arrival story or anything like that. Been in British Columbia all my life. Its funny, sometimes it feels like you can be from a place, know it inside out, but still feel like you dont quite fit, you know? But yeah, Canadian through and through, from the start.|Yeah, I'm a Canadian citizen. Born and raised, like I said. Its got its good points, but sometimes I wonder what life would be like somewhere else. Not that Im planning on going anywhere. Just, you know, late-night thoughts.|Not that Ive ever been told about. As far as I know, it was all pretty standard, no big dramas. My mom never mentioned anything out of the ordinary, just the usual stories of how happy they were, all that stuff. So, yeah, nothing noteworthy on the birth complications front.|Yeah, pretty much. I was walking and talking at the usual times, I guess. Had a few friends, did the normal kid stuff, playing outside, getting into minor trouble, all that. Never felt like I was behind or anything in those early days. It was all pretty standard, nothing that stood out as weird or different. Life was simpler back then, you know?|Nah, elementary school was alright for the most part. I was a decent student, got along okay with the other kids. Had my share of good times, nothing too heavy. It was later that things started getting complicated, but back in those days, it was mostly just normal kid stuff. Wish it couldve stayed that simple, to be honest.|Well, its kinda hard to dive into, you know? Theres been stuff. Like, the familys always been a bit of a mess, under the surface. My moms depression, that was a big shadow over everything. Made things feel unstable a lot of the time. And then there was just... I dunno, a lot of pressure, I guess. Pressure to be okay, to do well, to not add to the problems. Ended up dropping out of high school because it all just got too much. And theres been other stuff, darker moments, hard to talk about. Just a lot of things that pile up, make you feel like youre trapped in a tunnel with no light, you know?|Ah, high school... Feels like a lifetime ago. My marks were alright, I guess, mostly Bs and some Cs. Nothing spectacular, but I was getting by. Favorite class? Probably English. I liked the stories, the way you could dive into different worlds, different lives. It was an escape, you know? Made me think maybe I could do something with words, hence the whole TEFL thing later on. Its funny how those little bits stick with you, even when the rest feels like a blur.|Nah, after dropping out, I didnt go back to the traditional education route. Just felt like it wasnt for me, you know? But I didnt give up on learning altogether. Ended up getting into the TEFL (Teaching English as a Foreign Language) stuff online. Took some courses, got certified. Its not college or anything, but it felt right. Like I was building something for myself, in my own way. Teaching has been good for me, gives me a sense of purpose, and I get to use my love for English to help others. Its one of the few things that feels like it fits.|Before I got into the whole TEFL thing, I didnt really have much of a "traditional" work history. Did some odd jobs here and there, you know, the usual stuff young people do to make a bit of cash. Worked a bit in retail, a local grocery store, and did some delivery stuff for a while. Nothing that lasted too long or felt like it was going anywhere. Just bits and pieces to get by and figure stuff out. It was all before I found teaching English online, which, honestly, has been the first thing thats felt like a real job to me. Something I actually care about and want to stick with. So, no big companies or long-term positions, just a lot of hopping around until I landed on something good.|No, nothing like that. Been single most of the time. Had a few short-term things, but nothing that ever really stuck or felt serious. Its been tough, you know, with all the stuff going on with me. Makes it hard to let people in, or to even want to sometimes. Feels like a lot to ask of someone, to deal with all my baggage. So yeah, no marriages or long-term relationships. Just me, trying to figure out my own path without dragging anyone else into the mess.|Hobbies, huh? I guess Ive got a few things that keep me grounded. Readings always been big for me, like I mentioned with English class. Losing myself in a book, its one of the best escapes. And Ive gotten into writing a bit, too. Nothing major, just jotting down thoughts, stories, sometimes poetry if the mood strikes. Its therapeutic, helps me process stuff.

I also like hiking, being out in nature. British Columbias got some amazing places to explore, and its nice to just be out there, away from everything else. Clears the head, you know? And then theres music  listening, not playing. Wish I could play an instrument, but never really got around to learning. Musics another escape, a way to feel things deeply or just tune out the world for a bit.

So yeah, reading, writing, hiking, and music. Keeps me somewhat sane, gives me something to do with all the thoughts running around in my head.|On a stressful day, I kinda lean into those hobbies more. I might pick up a book and read for hours, just to get lost in a different world. Or Ill go for a long hike if the weathers good, try to clear my head with some fresh air and nature. Writings good for those really rough days, too, when my heads just full of stuff I cant seem to shake. Putting it all down on paper, its like letting some of the pressure out, you know?

Musics a big one as well. Ill put on some headphones, blast my favorite tunes, and just zone out. Sometimes its the only thing that can really calm me down, make me feel a bit more centered.

And if all else fails, I just try to remind myself that its okay to have bad days, that they pass. Might watch some mindless TV or cook something, just to keep my hands busy. Its all about finding those little things that help, even if its just for a moment.|I guess the main thing is just that Ive been struggling a lot, more than I usually let on. Its like, I try to keep all these plates spinning  the bulimia, dealing with my mood, trying to stay sober, managing the seizures  and it just feels like its only a matter of time before they all come crashing down. Ive got this resistance to doctors because it feels like Ive been through it all before, and nothing really changes. But deep down, I know I need help, I just dont know how to make it stick, you know?

And theres a part of me thats scared of getting better because I dont really know who I am without all this stuff. Its been my identity for so long, the sick guy, the one whos always struggling. But Im tired, man. Really tired. I want to believe theres a way out, that things can get better. I just dont know how to get there.

So yeah, thats where Im at. Just a lot of confusion, fear, and a tiny bit of hope that maybe this time will be different. Maybe Dr. Waters can see something others havent, or maybe Im just more ready to hear it now. Either way, Im here, giving it another shot. Thats got to count for something, right?

Each of these activities offers a unique way to engage with the world around you and provides a valuable balance to the complexities of daily life.

On a stressful day, what do you find helps you relax and unwind?|Finding solace in nature, immersing yourself in a project, and connecting with music are powerful ways to regain your balance and center yourself. It's clear you have a strong sense of what brings you peace and how to navigate back to a place of calm. Your strategies highlight the importance of engaging with both the external world and your inner self.

Before we conclude, is there anything else you feel the doctor needs to know or any additional comments you'd like to make?|Your resilience and openness to exploring new or different paths in search of well-being are truly admirable, Oscar. It's important to acknowledge both the caution that comes from past experiences and the willingness to remain engaged in the process of finding what works best for you. I'll ensure Dr. Hamilton understands your perspective and your commitment to continuing the journey toward better mental health, with an openness to trying new approaches as part of that process.

Thank you for taking the time to share your experiences and thoughts with me today. Your insights are invaluable and will greatly assist Dr. Hamilton in providing you with the most appropriate care. If there's nothing else you'd like to add, I wish you the best until your appointment. Goodbye, Oscar.
